    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1067"^^xsd:anyURI .

book:1068 a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:1068 ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2026-07-07T20:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "Susanna Clarke" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2020"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:isPartOf list:DublinLibrary ;
    schema:name "Piranesi" ;
    schema:review "The opening segment blasts you straight into a familiar feeling. Its a house with seemingly infinite rooms. There are variations, things of interest, and explorations. Hidden knowledge. Biomes. Wonders. What it reminded me of immediately was it someone had taken Borges' works and decided to really get into it. But there's more to this than just that. Towards the end, things collapse down into more predictable fantasies. But the writing is sharp, the nature of wonder and innocence and being human, that draws itself out in the confines of the House, is really the highlight. Can we see the wonders that pass by us everyday? Sometimes it takes another world to realise that."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1068"^^xsd:anyURI .

book:1069 a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:1069 ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2026-07-06T14:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "Simon Jimenez" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2020"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:isPartOf list:DublinLibrary ;
    schema:name "The Vanished Birds" ;
    schema:review "The setting of the book is definitely within the bounds of scifi, what with the ability of a boy to teleport to any place he wants. But the core of the book is what it means to be a human in a society -- especially one that functions capitalistically. The boy is now a resource, for the benefit of mankind's progress of course, and the characters lives and decisions are all invisibly moved by the hand that takes things with an immeasurably invisible force and is reluctant to return any of it. There are colonies, corporations, subservient governments, and humans stuck in this way of life. The writing could have been better, the story does move at a very slow pace. But its undeniable what the book is."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1069"^^xsd:anyURI .

