book:1070 a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:1070 ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2026-07-05T23:55:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating2 ;
    schema:author "Hao Jingfang" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2020"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:isPartOf list:DublinLibrary ;
    schema:name "Vagabonds" ;
    schema:review "The basic premise is that Mars has a colony that is a stand-in for China, and Earth for western ethos. Amidst this, we get some cultural exchange discussions which are supposed to discuss the egalitarian and moral values of both sides, their contrasts, and the necessities as justified by each, while also being biased to continue propogandeering their own side for continued existence. Intriguing in theory. But the book itself, which was quite long - twice as much, was filled with too much information, not an easy flowing story, and sometimes felt like a textbook with the characters being so flat and difficult to keep up with. Important events happen but we get no characterisations but the amount of information about cultural associations in even minor lessons is given several pages. This was a difficult read. Reminded me of Robinson and Le Guin in some of their works, which felt at least like they knew what they were after and you could feel the story take you there."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1070"^^xsd:anyURI .

book:1071 a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:1071 ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2026-07-08T23:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating2 ;
    schema:author "Courttia Newland" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2021"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:isPartOf list:DublinLibrary ;
    schema:name "A River Called Time" ;
    schema:review "This was a rather difficult book to read because it constantly felt like I was missing some context, some necessary background and understanding that would have made me realise the story and the events. The writing was not enjoyable and kept making me re-read things that I thought I had understood. The story itself seemed interesting, but the pacing and the characters felt underexplored. The themes, of capitalism, social discriminations, and revolution, were not particularly new nor novel."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1071"^^xsd:anyURI .

