book:923 a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:923 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2023-12-15T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating5 ;
    schema:author "Hannu Rajaniemi" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2010"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:isPartOf list:cork ;
    schema:name "The Quantum Thief" ;
    schema:review "This was enjoyable with its rich dense fully formed world built using post-human quantum technologies with its own politics and social economy, including philosophical implications such as 'immortality as communism' and 'privacy enforced by global techno-suits'. The story itself covers tropes from heists, classical detective, political turmoil, class warfare, and so much more. I ordered the two sequels right as I finished this. Excellent book, and a lot to unpack and enjoy. The way technology is described in action is cool. Less exposition and explanations and a lot of show but don't tell means I had to think (hard) on several things and what they could mean and how they could be developed and used. A clever and intelligent story that also rewards shallow reading just as much as a detailed introspection. This is up there with Accelerando and Neuromancer."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/923"^^xsd:anyURI .

book:924 a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:924 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2024-01-19T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating3 ;
    schema:author "Irene Vallejo" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2019"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookNonFiction ;
    schema:name "Papyrus: The Invention of Books in the Ancient World" ;
    schema:review "A book about books! That was the first thought when I saw the book in a bookshop, and being intrigued I bought it. Papyrus promises a history of how the first book was invented. However, I found it to be much much more about how the first libraries were set up rather than the history of how books actually were invented. So while interested, I wanted less of Mediteranian history and more about writing and the need to record, and cave paintings, stone inscriptions, and papyrus - the titular game changer when it came to writing. The book has very little on this. Still interesting because there is a rich history of libraries and books being the medium through which people sought knowledge and education."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/924"^^xsd:anyURI .

book:925 a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:925 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2023-12-31T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "Ed Yong" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2016"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookNonFiction ;
    schema:isPartOf list:cork ;
    schema:name "I Contain Multitudes: The Microbes Within Us and a Grander View of Life" ;
    schema:review "Interesting book about how life is abundant of examples of a shared existence with microbes from the smallest to the largest. And the necessity of their existence in shaping the processes of living. The title implies a human-centric narration, but the book has more content about others - plants, animals, and microbes - which made for an interesting and educational reading. Lots of cool examples - like watching a good documentary on TV without knowing what's coming up."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/925"^^xsd:anyURI .

