book:960 a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:960 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2024-12-24T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating3 ;
    schema:author "Alastair Reynolds" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2002"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "Redemption Ark" ;
    schema:review "A follow-up to the cruder but creative Revelation Space, this book followed a set of stereotypical characters down into space war with some crazy physics involved. Pushed the story forward, but felt so much like a slow moving filler that it was annoying at times. There were additional characters introduced whose portions simply served to remind that there is more interesting stuff waiting to happen, and hence diluted their existence within the story to providing a 'human angle'. Boring. What I found interesting was the pushing of boundaries when it came to physics and inter-planetary politics - that was cool. The bit at the end justifying the state of play (trying not to put spoilers here) was also cool but it came in too late and was too little. Let's see what books 3 and 4 hold in store."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/960"^^xsd:anyURI .

book:961 a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:961 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2024-12-29T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating3 ;
    schema:author "Alastair Reynolds" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2003"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "Absolution Gap" ;
    schema:review "Book 3 was a slight improvement over Book 2 which disappointed because there were not much details. Book 3 had some, but I didn't like the whole quasi-religious thing which was too long and too prolonged. There were also several deus-ex machina moments where we are expected to go - oh yes sure that just happened - and continue pretending that we're not going to revisit or question that. I'm talking in particular about the whole Hades matrix and weird alient stuff that the characters just don't bother going back to even though it literally gives them species saving technologies. Perhaps, these didn't need to be three separate books (Books 2 to 4) but could have been condensed down into to 1 or maybe even 2 smaller books? Feels like a lot of filler which doesn't have all that details and excitement which the first book did. Since I've got Book 4, let's see whether it ends on a high or a disappointment."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/961"^^xsd:anyURI .

book:962 a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:962 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2025-01-02T08:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating2 ;
    schema:author "Alastair Reynolds" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2021"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "Inhibitor Phase" ;
    schema:review "Utterly disappointing. This is the last book (as of now) in the Revelation Space universe. As such, one expects there to be a large payoff in terms of finishing up things from previous books, and to provide sufficient details to consider the plot 'complete'. The book starts off with a banger - makes one think this is going to be a good book. But no. Then we meander about from one plot armor-ladden situation to the next, all the while introducing random new things that have neither a background nor are they ever clarified in the end. What started off as an amazing book with an excellent world-building (Revelation Space) ends with every book getting progressively worse until we reach this tome of disappointment. The only solace in all this is that this is a rather shorter book as compared to the earlier ones - so there was less pages to finish the disappointment with."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/962"^^xsd:anyURI .

book:963 a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:963 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2025-04-07T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "Mary Doria Russell" ;
    schema:dateCreated "1998"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "Children of God" ;
    schema:review "The first book, The Sparrow, is one of my most memorable readings. Its an excellent introspection of religion and belief. So I was hyped to know there's a second book set in the same universe, and that I had found a copy in a second-hand bookshop. This book deals with the aftermath, with a new focus on the strange nature of the aliens and their culture in the first book. Less about religion, and more about the evolution of a culture to deal with its own horror (in the sense of humanity). I was a bit disappointed that this wasn't as shocking or thrilling as the first book, but there is a good commentary in here that is better laid out and less about one individual and more about civilisation in a broad way."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/963"^^xsd:anyURI .

book:964 a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:964 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2025-01-07T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "Iain M. Banks" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2000"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "Look to Windward" ;
    schema:review "Clever book that is set in the Culture universe. It is always amazing to read more about the Culture - it is one of the few fully fleshed out worlds which don't have a hangover from the current times, and where there is truly 'science' and 'fiction'. In this case, the book is set after the events in 'Consider Phlebas', where the war and its effects continue to show a deep impact on the psyche - not human specifically but generally the absurdities that manifest in any sentient being. But this was not a serious or depressing book - it was quite interesting to see where the story was going and that there was an interesting story to experience no matter what. Waiting to read the next Culture book."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/964"^^xsd:anyURI .

